1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:27,675
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:28,312 --> 00:00:40,533
homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:41,610 --> 00:00:55,066
trying to make a distinction or trying to talk about the two types of meditation that we find in all forms of Buddhism, Samatha and Vipassana.

4
00:00:55,085 --> 00:00:57,429
Samatha means peacefulness, quietening.

5
00:00:57,689 --> 00:00:58,950
Vipassana means insight.

6
00:01:00,531 --> 00:01:09,221
And I think to get an angle of it, it's always good to go back to the Buddha's own personal experience and how it comes across to us through the scriptures.

7
00:01:10,265 --> 00:01:19,355
So here we have a young man, he's probably in his mid-twenties, and he's slowly becoming disillusioned with life.

8
00:01:20,376 --> 00:01:30,248
He's living the good life, he belongs to a ruling family, although in later commentaries he's put up to this huge eastern potentate.

9
00:01:30,269 --> 00:01:32,712
He's just a local boss.

10
00:01:33,956 --> 00:02:01,905
a local head of a tribe who actually has to pay tribute to the king of Kosala so he's what you might call upper middle class how about that and he has a wife and an ordinary family life extended family life lots of cousins many of whom of course join him when he when he starts the order

11
00:02:04,180 --> 00:02:10,632
and of course the women join him eventually, and just about the time his son is born.

12
00:02:12,895 --> 00:02:28,163
From a sort of psychodynamic point of view, from our sort of Western psychology viewpoint, it's rather interesting that his own mother died when he was only a week old, and

13
00:02:29,610 --> 00:02:35,860
That must have had some psychological effects on him, even though it was his mother's sister who became his stepmother.

14
00:02:39,406 --> 00:02:43,512
And somehow he leaves just as his child is born.

15
00:02:43,973 --> 00:02:47,799
That's a rather interesting coincidence of facts, I'm sure.

16
00:02:49,100 --> 00:02:53,747
Freudians or Jungians might say something about that.

17
00:02:53,888 --> 00:02:53,948
But

18
00:02:55,531 --> 00:03:25,368
one perhaps could say that this trauma even in that young age the loss of your mother does create I think some imbalance in the psyche which begins to manifest in him in his early twenties what we would call an existential crisis leading to probably an identity crisis who knows and what brings it about is the

19
00:03:27,239 --> 00:03:53,634
realization a sort of sudden growing realization that you know once youth has passed once you've come out of the out of the fantasy of youth where things like sickness old age and death are very far away one isn't concerned with these things anyway concerned with good living

20
00:03:55,370 --> 00:04:13,776
But around about 25, that is a change of view, that something happens within us, most of us anyway, where we realize that in fact, you know, youth is passing as we know it, and we're looking ahead to a glorious, hopeful middle age.

21
00:04:16,160 --> 00:04:17,982
We start taking things seriously.

22
00:04:18,002 --> 00:04:24,752
We tend to take our pension, get married, take a career anyway.

23
00:04:25,492 --> 00:04:50,723
from the easiness of use so within that sort of context he comes to realize that actually in the end there's just sickness, old age and death and it's a sort of crisis which builds up in him to such a degree that it makes him go, it makes him leave

24
00:04:53,622 --> 00:05:18,346
But there's another side to it, which also reinforces that search, is that he's experienced, shall we say, what Blake would call the road of excess, I think that's how he puts it, the road of excess leads to the palace of wisdom.

25
00:05:19,221 --> 00:05:25,009
At some point, when he's had all his parties and he's had a good time, he sees the vanity of it.

26
00:05:25,189 --> 00:05:28,074
He sees the other side of it, the emptiness of it.

27
00:05:30,197 --> 00:05:41,812
It's expressed in a visual sense that he wakes up at the end of a big carousing and just sees these dishevelled bodies and maybe the smell of sickness and who knows what.

28
00:05:44,076 --> 00:05:45,937
And that sort of...

29
00:05:46,507 --> 00:05:50,413
gives him the other side of pleasure, you see, the downside of pleasure.

30
00:05:50,694 --> 00:06:04,233
Psychologically, remember, this indulgence brings about frustration when you can't get what you want, the grief when you lose what you've got, and the anxiety when you've got what you've got and you're afraid to lose it.

31
00:06:04,254 --> 00:06:07,057
So all that psychology is in there, you see.

32
00:06:07,077 --> 00:06:10,642
And we can say that he was waking up to that fact that

33
00:06:12,495 --> 00:06:17,824
The life he was leading had this deeper emptiness to it.

34
00:06:17,845 --> 00:06:31,466
One could say that he hadn't found any real purpose in the family life that he was leading, in the sort of career that was being offered to him as a kshatriya, a warrior caste, a ruler.

35
00:06:35,394 --> 00:06:38,283
And so there comes this crisis point.

36
00:06:38,764 --> 00:06:40,247
We know about crisis, don't we?

37
00:06:40,267 --> 00:06:42,153
A financial crisis.

38
00:06:42,954 --> 00:06:44,459
He's having a psychological crisis.

39
00:06:45,442 --> 00:06:46,285
And so he leaves.

40
00:06:48,850 --> 00:06:51,278
Now he wouldn't have left if he didn't have somewhere to go.

41
00:06:52,286 --> 00:07:05,103
And the thing was that just as in the 70s there was a great movement of hippies searching for love, in those days there was quite a movement of people searching for the answer to life.

42
00:07:06,485 --> 00:07:16,218
In the Hindu, what we call Hinduism, the Vedas, there was this slow growing new literature, the Upanishads,

43
00:07:17,802 --> 00:07:47,690
which sort of manifests this questioning of the age it was also an age of a change in the culture movement away from pastoral societies dotted here and there with local rulers and things like that to a city based civilization in which there grew a merchant class which had not been there before a rich merchant class that began to have power and kingship which the Buddha didn't particularly like

44
00:07:49,442 --> 00:07:52,889
He preferred the more democratic meetings of pastoral societies.

45
00:07:56,716 --> 00:08:07,096
So there's ferment, you know, there's change happening in society, not perhaps as vicious as we've experienced, but definitely some dislocation going on.

46
00:08:08,156 --> 00:08:37,572
and there were these groups of men very rare for women to do it because of the dangers involved and of course the sexism involved too who went out into the forests and tried to find the meaning of life that was their job and one of the strains of understanding which empowered them was the

47
00:08:39,544 --> 00:08:42,369
the belief in rebirth, the belief in reincarnation.

48
00:08:45,251 --> 00:08:53,562
And there were many sort of answers to it, but it was the horror of having to be reborn again into this life.

49
00:08:53,582 --> 00:09:07,559
Remember these times are a bit harder, you know, like there's no videos, there's no DVDs, there's no cars, I mean it's, you know, it's sort of dog work, you know, like you're out in the field digging and you come back, what do you do, you know.

50
00:09:07,979 --> 00:09:12,544
Like, well, we're going to go tonight, you know.

51
00:09:13,647 --> 00:09:20,956
The only entertainments, you might say, were the occasional, the big entertainments, the occasional military parades.

52
00:09:20,975 --> 00:09:32,291
And, believe it or not, the holy men, who would turn up in their parks, in their shrines, and everybody would go out on a full moon night and ask questions, and they'd do some chanting and stuff like that.

53
00:09:32,331 --> 00:09:32,772
That was...

54
00:09:34,945 --> 00:09:40,631
In a sense, the fullness of their entertainment, I suppose, apart from the usual things, playing games.

55
00:09:45,759 --> 00:09:57,312
And the idea that one had to be reborn again and again and again and go through this horror, because in those days, of course, sickness, old age and death wasn't something that happened in hospitals or shut away somewhere.

56
00:09:58,153 --> 00:09:59,855
The dead were taken to charnel ground.

57
00:10:00,336 --> 00:10:01,639
You could see the bodies rotting.

58
00:10:01,979 --> 00:10:04,361
When the wind changed, you knew where it was coming from.

59
00:10:04,746 --> 00:10:33,014
like it was there it was in the open as you might still see in India you see when you go there that's one of the great things about India it doesn't disguise these things so this whole idea of having to come back to this again so one was looking for an escape see where was the escape and that was the atmosphere which the Buddha left home you know

60
00:10:33,298 --> 00:10:36,485
And I dare say that when he left, he didn't say, I'm off for good.

61
00:10:37,647 --> 00:10:49,408
So I said, well, I'm just nipping off for a little while and checking this thing out, see if I can find an answer to my deep sense of, my deep disturbance, you know.

62
00:10:51,493 --> 00:10:56,201
I remember when I told my mother that I was going to become a monk, you see.

63
00:10:56,957 --> 00:11:03,029
She collapsed into this such a deep weeping, came from the sort of deepest part of her heart.

64
00:11:03,210 --> 00:11:04,011
Even I started crying.

65
00:11:06,076 --> 00:11:09,842
So I gave her a hug and said, Mum, it's only for three years.

66
00:11:09,923 --> 00:11:13,649
And she stopped like that.

67
00:11:14,643 --> 00:11:19,672
And of course, you have to put it in the context of Catholicism because priests are around.

68
00:11:19,711 --> 00:11:21,034
You can see a priest there.

69
00:11:21,054 --> 00:11:22,837
But if you become a monk, that's it.

70
00:11:22,878 --> 00:11:24,159
You cut your tie.

71
00:11:24,220 --> 00:11:25,763
You enter the monastery.

72
00:11:25,783 --> 00:11:26,784
And nobody ever sees you again.

73
00:11:26,965 --> 00:11:28,307
I think they've softened up on that now.

74
00:11:28,327 --> 00:11:31,033
I think they can see people once a month or something.

75
00:11:31,052 --> 00:11:32,335
But in the old days, that was it.

76
00:11:32,355 --> 00:11:32,615
Left.

77
00:11:33,216 --> 00:11:34,018
Collapsed, you see.

78
00:11:35,145 --> 00:11:38,592
So I dare say there was a lot of gnashing of teeth.

79
00:11:38,812 --> 00:11:39,715
His parents wept.

80
00:11:40,056 --> 00:11:42,620
In later tales they say how his parents wept at his leaving.

81
00:11:42,681 --> 00:11:43,722
His wife wept.

82
00:11:44,004 --> 00:11:44,865
Everybody wept, you see.

83
00:11:45,826 --> 00:11:46,950
And I'm sure he said, well, I'm only going.

84
00:11:46,970 --> 00:11:47,871
I'll be back in a bit.

85
00:11:49,014 --> 00:11:49,855
We're going to see what it's like.

86
00:11:51,558 --> 00:11:57,070
So he goes off and joins these ascetics living in the forest.

87
00:11:59,412 --> 00:12:07,846
And the people he goes to, the first two teachers, teach him what we now call the jhana, what we now call absorption meditations.

88
00:12:09,429 --> 00:12:20,168
And when you practice this Samatha type of meditation, you're creating a state of mind.

89
00:12:21,269 --> 00:12:23,934
But the beauty of it is that although you begin

90
00:12:24,995 --> 00:12:39,457
with an outside object, either a candle flame, you all know that, or a circle, or an inner object like a mantra, or an inner object like your breath, it's still an object.

91
00:12:40,700 --> 00:12:46,428
You're only using it to bring about a certain laser quality to the mind.

92
00:12:47,842 --> 00:13:16,634
and i think you'll know that when the mind begins to concentrate bliss arises naturally it's just the quality of the mind as it concentrates sort of an energy in it and we experience it as a certain type of inner happiness and uh... the first teacher really took him right through what we now recognize as the

93
00:13:17,256 --> 00:13:42,183
the jhanas, the rupa-jhanas and the arupa-jhanas and now the rupa-jhanas are those states that you get by deepening your concentration until as it were the mental state leaves the body goes inward as it were and finds its own joy and then even leaves that to find a perfect peace

94
00:13:42,772 --> 00:13:48,419
This is not the equanimity of the seven factors of enlightenment.

95
00:13:49,201 --> 00:13:50,582
They use the same word, you see.

96
00:13:50,623 --> 00:13:52,625
These words are used variously.

97
00:13:52,644 --> 00:13:54,467
It's the same word, but they have slightly different meanings.

98
00:13:56,971 --> 00:14:04,260
And then, leaving that, as it were, one enters into a stranger place where there's no object at all.

99
00:14:04,701 --> 00:14:11,009
So right up until that point, there's always an object, a light, the feeling, a sense, there's something there.

100
00:14:11,090 --> 00:14:12,491
But when that disappears...

101
00:14:13,619 --> 00:14:22,720
And this consciousness, as it were, if I want a better word, flips into a different state and there's nothing there.

102
00:14:23,782 --> 00:14:33,163
And those places are called infinite space, infinite consciousness, infinite nothingness.

103
00:14:34,898 --> 00:14:48,062
these relate, I'm talking now to people just a little bit who know the Dharma a bit deeper, these relate to the four khandhas, you see.

104
00:14:48,081 --> 00:14:57,057
So when you're into that area of space of nothingness, it's out of that nothingness that the sankhara arises, the manifestations of mind.

105
00:14:58,642 --> 00:15:14,202
when you're into that space of consciousness you're at the beginning of the vijnana process of consciousness which manifests eventually as one of the aggregates when you're in the space

106
00:15:15,398 --> 00:15:16,759
Everywhere there's just space.

107
00:15:17,279 --> 00:15:20,484
You're at the subtle level of Vedana feeling.

108
00:15:22,206 --> 00:15:35,823
And when you're at neither perception nor not perception, that's the beginning level of perception as that consciousness descends into the mind and finally coagulates into what we call physical body.

109
00:15:37,245 --> 00:15:44,815
So that process that a person might go through, it has its own insightfulness as you pass through it.

110
00:15:46,802 --> 00:15:53,773
And the Buddha took this with his teacher and became an adept and the teacher said, please join me.

111
00:15:55,176 --> 00:16:09,096
And he said, no, he said, although I've done all this and they're very blissful states and all that, but it's not really answered my question as to is there an end to suffering.

112
00:16:09,116 --> 00:16:11,941
Now that's the core thing which I should have mentioned earlier.

113
00:16:12,861 --> 00:16:16,067
The quest was, is there an end to suffering?

114
00:16:16,148 --> 00:16:24,623
And that, you know, eventually puts his whole teaching just in three words in the texts, dukkha, dukkha nirod, suffering and the end of suffering.

115
00:16:25,294 --> 00:16:29,423
This dukkha, of course, has a very wide meaning.

116
00:16:29,523 --> 00:16:36,076
Here I've translated it as suffering, dissatisfaction, sense of lack, meaninglessness.

117
00:16:37,038 --> 00:16:46,576
It's the whole gamut of human suffering, from the smallest little disturbance to the deepest despair and horror.

118
00:16:49,779 --> 00:17:17,154
so he leaves that teacher and he finds another one who takes him just one step further than these Arupa Jhanas and there becomes an adept and again he's asked to teach but he says no, he leaves you see so although he's practiced these concentration meditations although he's taken them to the fullest development

119
00:17:17,826 --> 00:17:39,395
recognized by his own teachers there's just something lacking there's something which has not been undermined which is still causing him suffering causing him some feeling of dissatisfaction so now he tries

120
00:17:41,484 --> 00:17:53,696
a different tack, which seemingly he gets from an elder teacher, a contemporary teacher, the Nagantha, the leader of the Jains.

121
00:17:56,338 --> 00:18:04,686
Now his understanding was that bad karma was accrued even when he didn't mean it.

122
00:18:05,106 --> 00:18:07,829
So you know that Jain monks go around with a whisk.

123
00:18:08,012 --> 00:18:12,580
and make sure that there's no bugs that they're going to tread on, accidentally, see.

124
00:18:12,601 --> 00:18:20,535
So their understanding is that even accidentally, you still cause suffering, and therefore there's going to be a karmic comeback, you see.

125
00:18:20,555 --> 00:18:28,890
And the real problem lay, and this runs right the way through, really, Indian literature, in desire, trishna, you know.

126
00:18:30,237 --> 00:18:37,145
So one had to live the absolute ascetic life, deny the body any pleasure because there was a danger.

127
00:18:37,526 --> 00:18:47,598
He didn't seemingly make a distinction between pleasurable sensations and the attachment or desire that you have to them.

128
00:18:49,181 --> 00:18:54,186
So one had to, as it were, undermine that whole process.

129
00:18:54,207 --> 00:18:55,788
And if you think about it,

130
00:18:59,042 --> 00:19:01,025
Pleasures come through the body, don't they?

131
00:19:01,685 --> 00:19:06,550
So you begin to blame the body for your problems.

132
00:19:08,272 --> 00:19:15,902
And you fast, you sit in front of very hot fires.

133
00:19:17,763 --> 00:19:23,430
You do all sorts of ascetic practices which are meant to steal you against the pleasures of the body, you see.

134
00:19:26,836 --> 00:19:37,152
So he took this, again, he seemingly took it to his own personal end, like he couldn't go any further with it, and basically he just got thin.

135
00:19:39,234 --> 00:19:41,518
And he said he could hold his spine through his stomach.

136
00:19:43,541 --> 00:19:45,384
That's how thin he was.

137
00:19:45,403 --> 00:19:50,132
And he hadn't, and again he sort of wasn't achieving anything.

138
00:19:50,511 --> 00:19:54,278
Like it is a question, this fundamental question about

139
00:19:55,961 --> 00:20:01,888
suffering about meaningfulness, had not been answered.

140
00:20:03,951 --> 00:20:07,255
And he's with five companions, remember, at this time.

141
00:20:07,296 --> 00:20:12,862
They're going for it, helter-skelter, and they're really whipping themselves and getting into it big time.

142
00:20:14,604 --> 00:20:15,244
And so he leaves.

143
00:20:16,906 --> 00:20:21,092
So now, in the opening stanzas of his very first talk,

144
00:20:22,522 --> 00:20:29,011
He says that the life devoted to sensual pleasure is base, ignoble, waste of time, leading nowhere.

145
00:20:30,574 --> 00:20:36,020
And the life devoted to self-mortification, which is not renunciation.

146
00:20:36,060 --> 00:20:40,867
Renunciation is not doing something to see your attachment.

147
00:20:40,887 --> 00:20:47,636
Self-mortification is based on self-punishment, self-negation in that sort of bad way.

148
00:20:50,012 --> 00:21:17,353
rejection of life as it is in a way and that self-mortification was also just painful he said and led nowhere at least the first one was pleasant and led nowhere but this was painful and led nowhere but he doesn't he doesn't say that the jhanas that the other stuff that he learnt about developing the qualities of mind was a waste of time and that becomes part of his system

149
00:21:20,776 --> 00:21:41,214
but we can at least I can get a sense of his despair when he leaves his companion who was he gonna do he can't go home because it would just go back into that emptiness bad emptiness he's been to all these teachers and

150
00:21:41,988 --> 00:21:50,517
He's talked a lot to people, and you can see from his teaching that he knows all the local philosophies of the time and the psychologies of the time.

151
00:21:51,057 --> 00:21:53,220
They learned it.

152
00:21:53,240 --> 00:21:55,482
And he's tried everything, and he's got nowhere to go.

153
00:21:58,365 --> 00:22:07,134
So I imagine that when he sat on that road along which Sujata came, he was in a state of real existential despair.

154
00:22:13,307 --> 00:22:21,459
And when Sujata comes along with her rice pudding, or well, rice cakes, she takes pity on this man.

155
00:22:21,479 --> 00:22:23,942
I mean, you know, in the scriptures they soup it up.

156
00:22:24,103 --> 00:22:29,990
She's going to offer this to a god and sees the Bodhisattva who is resplendent and believes that this is the god.

157
00:22:30,009 --> 00:22:32,733
But actually, he must be looking miserable.

158
00:22:33,275 --> 00:22:36,378
She thought, well, maybe he needs it more than this god.

159
00:22:38,553 --> 00:23:04,054
and we all know the salvific effect of rice pudding enormous in its power so having tasted it he sort of feels better and around about that time he has this memory of his father doing a prying ceremony he's a child and there's something about the way

160
00:23:05,299 --> 00:23:32,303
he remembers there's something about the way he's looking at his father doing the plowing ceremony which offers him another way of seeking the end seeking the answer to his predicament and that's why I've got these pictures the little baby at the back there on the board

161
00:23:32,839 --> 00:23:37,124
was on a poster, was on an advert in Birmingham Station.

162
00:23:38,545 --> 00:23:40,487
And I came out of the train, I saw this.

163
00:23:40,507 --> 00:23:42,788
It was part of an advert.

164
00:23:42,808 --> 00:23:46,612
And I went home, came all the way back to Birmingham Station to take that picture.

165
00:23:46,632 --> 00:23:52,217
I'd probably broken some sort of publication rights, but... And I thought it was a fantastic book.

166
00:23:52,258 --> 00:24:00,585
Make sure you have a look at that because what it expresses is that way of looking

167
00:24:00,970 --> 00:24:02,152
and the moment of seeing.

168
00:24:02,972 --> 00:24:11,724
And the little girl in the other picture was given to me by a friend in Dublin, Dennis.

169
00:24:12,987 --> 00:24:19,095
This is a picture that brought into the Irish times.

170
00:24:19,115 --> 00:24:30,471
And there was an opening of this, what do you call it, where they put trees and little animals, nature, nature reserves.

171
00:24:31,041 --> 00:24:48,265
And you can see that she's reaching out to a plant to see what there is there, but the look on her face, if you look at it, has both an intense interest, but also a sense of trepidation, a sense of fear of the unknown, like if I see this, what will happen?

172
00:24:50,728 --> 00:24:53,510
So that comes first, and the baby face comes second.

173
00:24:53,912 --> 00:24:54,011
Yeah.

174
00:24:55,307 --> 00:25:03,999
So here's this child watching his father doing a praying ceremony and there is a tremendous interest in what his father is doing.

175
00:25:04,819 --> 00:25:09,746
And that interest draws him into an absorbed state.

176
00:25:09,987 --> 00:25:10,707
He's just looking.

177
00:25:11,067 --> 00:25:12,630
And you see it in children, don't you?

178
00:25:12,829 --> 00:25:16,074
You see it when their jaw drops and their eyes become fixated.

179
00:25:17,256 --> 00:25:21,500
And you can't shake them out of it unless you give them a clip on the back of the head.

180
00:25:23,438 --> 00:25:51,993
and that's it, that's the pure openness of that intuitive intelligence just receiving so that's why I try to stress this quiet abiding because there you drop your preconceptions you drop your ideas, you drop your concepts, you drop your history dropping your history and you lay yourself open just observing, feeling, experiencing what's happening right now

181
00:25:54,386 --> 00:26:20,377
so there was something in that looking which raised again that encouraged him to have another go and he was so certain that this would actually be the answer that he makes a determination doesn't need to sit under the tree and either die or find you know find the answer to his to this existential problem of suffering

